or a4. The game went} 8... O-O 9. Bg5 Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 {and now the small
combination} 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nxd5 $1 {underlined the cons of ...a6, ...b5.}
12... Qxd5 13. Be4 $18) 6. exd5 (6. Bg5 c4 7. Be2 Be7 8. e5 Nfd7 9. Bxe7 Qxe7
{looks reasonably OK for Black. If White could blast the queenside blockade
with} 10. b3 b5 11. a4 {then there would be some advantage for him but Black can
keep the position closed with} 11... b4 12. Na2 c3 {and White's knight on a2
looks rather silly. Here ...a6 proved to be a useful move as it was essential to
keep the blockade.}) 6... exd5 7. O-O c4 8. Be2 Bb4 $1 (8... Be7 {is imprecise
and White is able to keep a small plus.} 9. b3 Bb4 (9... b5 $6 10. bxc4 bxc4
11. Ne5 {is also not great for Black. The knight on e5 is quite annoying and
Black has to resort to some pretty artificial maneuvers in order to get rid of
it.} 11... O-O 12. Rb1 Qc7 ({Black would very much like to play} 12... Nbd7
{immediately but White has} 13. Nc6 Qe8 14. Bf3 {and Black's position is just
about to fall apart.}) 13. Bf4 Bd6 14. Bf3 Be6 15. Bg5 $1 {White is indirectly
putting even more pressure on the d5-pawn and Black will be unable to keep
things under control anymore.} 15... Nbd7 (15... Bxe5 {loses a pawn for no
compensation} 16. dxe5 Qxe5 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Ra7 20. Qxc4
$16) 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. Bxf6 gxf6 {Black's pawn formation is ruined and White can
immediately steer the game into a clearly favourable endgame with} 18. Nxd5 Bxd5
19. Bxd5 Bxh2+ 20. Kxh2 Qxd5 {where the passed d4-pawn and broken Black kingside
give him a long-term advantage.}) (9... cxb3 10. axb3 O-O 11. Ne5 $14 {is also
nice for White. His pawn structure is more compact and the d5-pawn is a weakness
that will need constant care.}) 10. Bd2 cxb3 11. axb3 O-O 12. Na4 Bxd2 13. Qxd2
$14 {is very similar to the 9...cxb3 line and the same observations apply here
too. Black's isolated pawn on d5 will be a constant source of trouble for him.})
9. Bg5 {Moving to d2 would be quite passive so White at least hopes to take the
bishop pair.} 9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 Qd6 $13 {This position is similar to the
positions arising in the Winawer variation. White's e5-pawn and Black's e6-pawn
are not present here which makes it easier for Black to develop pieces. Note
that thanks to the presence of a Black pawn on c4 the Be2 movements are quite
restricted.}) 5... Nfd7 6. Ne2 c5 7. c3 Nc6 {is a position in the spirit of the
last chapter and Black can actually reach it using the 3...Nf6 move order too.
There are more troubling options than .. . a6 in the 3...Nf6 system, but
nevertheless I'd like to take a more simple approach after 3...a6.} 8. a3 c4
{Black is trying to claim that losing time with ...a6 is not so important in a
closed position. He will be one tempo short after} 9. Nf4 Na5 10. Nd2 {though.
White is preparing a quick ambush of Black's kingside.} (10. Be3 {would be nice
