advantage. Students can choose from 3 options which I have given here based on
their taste.} 9. Nf3 {White can opt for playing a middlegame with queens too.} (
9. Qf3 {steers the game into a favourable ending.} 9... Nf6 10. Qxd5 Nxd5
11. Nf3 O-O 12. Bd2 {White's bishop pair is pretty strong here as the position
is relatively open and play takes place on both wings (a pair of knights is
unable to maneuvre quickly from one side to another). Another thing going for
White is the fact that the pawn structure is unbalanced and it usually is easier
to create a passed pawn with a queenside majority than the other way around.}
12... Nc6 13. Rhe1 Ncb4 {Trying to shake White's setup up a bit but to no
avail.} 14. Bc4 Be6 15. Nd4 Rac8 16. Bb3 Nc6 17. Nxe6 fxe6+ 18. Kg1 Nd4 19. c3
{Sometimes it is half-jokingly told that the biggest advantage of a bishop pair
is that at the right time one of the bishops can be favourably exchanged. It
certainly applies here as White is happy to trade his bishop pair edge for a
weakness on e6.} 19... Nxb3 20. axb3 $14 {e6 is indeed quite weak and Black's
