$16) 7. Qxd5 Qe7+ 8. Nge2 {Had White's bishop been still on f1, his pieces would
be a bit clumsy. Here Black can only delay the inevitable - eventually White
will castle kingside and enjoy his full extra pawn advantage.} 8... Bxb5 9. Nxb5
Nf6 10. Qf5 O-O 11. Bg5 {Another important move. Because of the positional
threat of Bxf6 Black has to develop his queen's knight to d7 instead of the more
active c6. White needs just one move (Nc3) to be able to castle so he can afford
one more developing move instead.} 11... Nbd7 12. Nc3 $16 {White is a healthy
pawn up and Black has no compensation here. It would be a bit different with a
knight on c6 instead when Black would be able to speculate a bit with ...Nb4 so
remember to force it to go to d7 with Bg5!}) (5... d4 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7. Qe2+ $1 {
It is important to include Qe2+ otherwise White would lose a piece to Qa5+.} (
7. Ne4 $2 Qa5+ $19) 7... Be6 8. Ne4 Nf6 (8... Qd5 9. Nh3 $1 $16 {White can play
