both the Black queen and bishop. Especially as} 9... Bxh3 $2 10. Nf6+ { delivers
a killing double check and in fact mate in 2 as well.}) 9. Bg5 { Black is
somehow fishing for compensation but White's last precise moves feel like
hammering new nails into Black's coffin.} 9... Be7 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 {A sad choice.
Do you let your opponent's knight land on d6 or do you cripple your pawns
forever?} (10... gxf6 11. O-O-O f5 12. Nd6+ $1 {It is quite usual to convert
positional advantage into a material one, but you should not be afraid of the
reverse conversion as well. Black's position is in ruins even when the material
is equal.} 12... Bxd6 13. cxd6 Qxd6 14. Nf3 O-O-O 15. Bxc6 Qxc6 16. Rhe1 $16
{Taking on d4 is just a formality. Black, in a broken position and being down in
material, will have to struggle.} ({The slightly more hasty} 16. Nxd4 Qxg2
17. Nxe6 fxe6 18. Qxe6+ Kb8 19. Qe5+ Ka8 20. Qf4 $16 {with a clear extra pawn is
also extra good for White.})) 11. Nd6+ Kf8 12. Nf3 $16 {White is simply much
better thanks to his extra pawn and Black's king being stuck on f8. It will take
Black some time to get his pieces coordinated at least a little bit so finding
decent compensation for the missing pawn is out the of question.}) 6. Be3 {We
are keeping it as simple as possible. White is holding on to his extra pawn and
at the same time makes good developing moves. Perfect.} 6... Nc6 7. Nf3 Be7
8. Be2 $16 {It is quite hard for Black to get to the c5-pawn as the d5-square
needs protection too. After castling White can stabilize the pawn with a3-b4.} *

