1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. exd5 {Once again there are several options to
play for White against 3... Bb4. I chose this simple set-up, interestingly I
already played this system against GM Caruana in St. Louis February 2019 and GM
Rapport in March 2019 in Prague.} 4... exd5 {One might argue that the position
is too symmetrical for White to claim an advantage. However there are many
examples of seemingly dry opening positions that suddenly came back into fashion
in modern chess. The supposedly 'boring' exchange Slav which is being employed
even at top level these days could be one example. Exchanging on d5 as early as
on move 3 is not completely without poison as well and there are some games
where White was able to pose Black some problems. Our situation is a bit more
advantageous as the b4-bishop is not placed so well.} 5. Bd3 Nc6 { is a rather
ambitious try to refute White's set-up altogether by targeting the d4-pawn.}
6. Nf3 Nge7 7. O-O Bf5 {is a bit of a hybrid system for Black. Many classical
books on the opening recommend him to develop the knight to e7 versus a knight
on f3 and vice versa to develop the knight to f6 versus Ne2. It is a bit
superficial to suppose that Black will just manage to exchange all the pieces
and make a draw as White has quite some potential on the kingside anyway.}
8. Ne2 $1 {Now the ...Bb4-move looks really useless whereas the knight is
preparing to switch to attacking the kingside.} 8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 O-O 10. c3 {We
should protect the d4-square well and the bishop might retreat all the way to e7
if we mix up the move order, so we better play c3 straight away.} 10... Bd6
11. Ng5 $1 {It is time to storm the kingside. Black is naturally hesitant to
weaken the kingside with a move like} 11... g6 {because after} 12. Qh3 {the only
defence against the checkmate on h7 is the ugly-looking} 12... h5 {However White
will force him to make some concessions one way or another.} *

