continue with active development.} 10. Re1 {It is especially important that the
dark-squared bishop is not contributing to defense of the a3-f8 diagonal, mainly
the e7-square.} 10... Nxd4 11. g4 Nxf3+ 12. Qxf3 Bxc3 { Everything is forced as
retreating the bishop to g6 loses straight away.} 13. bxc3 Bg6 14. Qe3 $1 {It is
paramount that we stop the Black king from running away from the center. Then we
plan to increase the pressure on the dark squares with a4 and Ba3.} 14... Kf8
15. a4 Bxd3 16. cxd3 Nc6 {Black managed not to get his knight pinned with Ba3
but we can alter our plans a little bit here.} 17. c4 $1 {It makes a lot of
sense to open the position more when we are attacking the enemy king.}
17... dxc4 18. dxc4 {with great compensation for White. We can decide whether we
put the bishop on b2 or a3, then we develop the a1-rook to the center with Rd1.
Black has a very tough defensive task and let us just note that he cannot try to
simplify with} 18... Qd4 $2 {due to} 19. Ba3+ Kg8 20. Qe8+ $1 {mating on the
next move.} *

