is too symmetrical for White to claim an advantage. However there are many
examples of seemingly dry opening positions that suddenly came back into fashion
in modern chess. The supposedly 'boring' exchange Slav which is being employed
even at top level these days could be one example. Exchanging on d5 as early as
on move 3 is not completely without poison as well and there are some games
where White was able to pose Black some problems. Our situation is a bit more
advantageous as the b4-bishop is not placed so well.} 5. Bd3 Nc6 { is a rather
ambitious try to refute White's set-up altogether by targeting the d4-pawn.}
6. Nf3 Bg4 {The idea is simple, Black wants to capture on d4.} 7. O-O {The
timid} 7... Nge7 {delaying the capture on d4, does not score very well for Black
in practice.} 8. h3 Bh5 {is also not so great. We kick the other bishop too
with} 9. a3 Bxc3 {This is a bit of a concession as White is getting the bishop
pair advantage immediately. Nevertheless in practice it is not so easy to
convert it without exact opening knowledge.} 10. bxc3 Bg6 {is not very testing.
The pressure on the center has been softened so we can repair our pawn structure
with} 11. c4 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 dxc4 13. Qxc4 {and enjoy the stronger central
position, let's say} 13... O-O 14. Bf4 Qd7 15. Qd3 Rfe8 16. Rad1 Rad8 17. c4 $14
*

